Authorization of appropriations for United States Customs Service for enhanced activities along the Southwest border. Authorization of appropriations for the United States Customs Service to enhance border investigative resources, combat drug smuggling and money laundering, process cargo efficiently, and reduce traffic waiting times on the Southwest border. Appropriations include $467,320,000 for fiscal year 2002, $417,832,000 for fiscal year 2003, and necessary sums for subsequent fiscal years. For fiscal year 2002, $158,320,000 is allocated for acquiring narcotics enforcement, cargo processing, and counterterrorism technology along the Southwest border. This includes funding for mobile truck gamma ray systems, high energy pallet gamma ray systems, higher energy truck x-ray upgrades, and contract nonintrusive inspection equipment operators. $41.3 million for contract nonintrusive inspection equipment operators, $12 million for inspection technology maintenance, $800,000 for Industry Partnership Programs expansion, $1.6 million for canine kennel construction, $500,000 for replacement of canines, $1 million for narcotics automated targeting systems maintenance, $2.5 million for 10 x-ray vans, $1.5 million for 15 tool trucks, $3.5 million to refurbish existing x-ray vans and tool trucks, $600,000 for 50 contraband detection kits. $600,000 for 50 contraband detection kits;
$1,000,000 for 20 remote watch surveillance camera systems;
$1,000,000 for 40 counterspotter surveillance systems;
$2,500,000 for 10 truck license plate reader systems;
$1,600,000 for 40 narcotics particle detectors;
$14,800,000 for 29 land border vehicle targeting systems;
$3,000,000 for 250 under vehicle inspection systems;
$1,500,000 for 5 outbound passenger facilities and canopies;
$1,500,000 for 300 work station replacements; In addition to previous allocations, funds are designated for various security equipment including explosive vapor trace detectors, radiation pager detectors, radiation identification devices, and detection training. $15,832,000 is allocated annually for these purposes starting from fiscal year 2003. The Commissioner of Customs may use funds allocated for equipment for technologically superior equipment other than specified in subsection (b). The Commissioner of Customs can reallocate up to 10 percent of funds specified in subsection (b) for equipment to obtain technologically superior equipment at the same or lower cost. In fiscal years 2002 and 2003, $79,000,000 and $172,000,000 respectively will be allocated for increasing personnel at the Southwest border to reduce waiting times and enhance drug enforcement efforts. In fiscal years 2002 and 2003, $230,000,000 each year will be allocated for improving Customs Service facilities at ports of entry on the Southwest Border. Amounts authorized for the United States Customs Service by subsection (a) are additional to any other authorized amounts by law.
